# 2026-06-11

## Phase 3 scoped — phase-3.md created

Phase 2 closed (slice 9 cp3, 2026-06-10). Did Phase 3 scope discovery across
ARCHITECTURE / DECISIONS / CLAUDE / WORKFLOW / README / the phase-0..2 deferred
sections / deferred.md, then drafted **`docs/modules/phase-3.md`** mirroring
phase-2.md's structure.

**Phase 3 = finance + first deploy.** ARCHITECTURE §9 defines its success as
"first paying customer", which requires a deployed product — so deploy work and
the finance build run in parallel. September 2026 is the real deadline.

Locked decisions (in the doc): first deploy in scope; pilot acquisition is
operational not a build deliverable; Paystack + Fly.io/Neon/Vercel/R2 are
user-provisioned prerequisites (each gates the slice that needs it); NDPR NG-only
deferred; SaaS subscription billing deferred to Phase 4+ (Phase 3 is school→parent
fee collection only); thin payroll in; online (Paystack) + offline (manual cash/
POS/transfer) payments; `bursar` role ships; auth hardening is a prerequisite
slice before any finance slice.

Substantive refinement banked: **finance flexibility** = school-defined
`FeeCategory` + scoped `FeeItem` (level/arm/term/year, nulls = "all") + curated
`DiscountRule` types (5 pre-built, typed params, per-type eval functions — NOT a
DSL) + **snapshot-on-issue** invoices (issued invoices freeze the fee/discount
state; editing fees later doesn't touch them — the slice-6 snapshot-drift pattern
applied to money).

Slice order front-loads de-risking: pre-deploy + in-container PDF memory gate
(slice 1) → auth hardening (slice 2) → audit partitioning (slice 3) → fee catalog
→ discounts → invoices → manual payments → **Paystack (the meaty, risky one)** →
installments → debtors → refunds → payroll → expenses → dashboard → Phase-3 close
(slice 15). ~27-30 cps, ~38-48 build days; ~65 weekdays to mid-September — tight,
with late slices (expenses, dashboard, installments) as deferral valves.

Estimate realism flagged: the ARCHITECTURE "3-4 weeks" quote predates the
flexibility requirements + "includes first deploy" and is optimistic by a wide
margin; the doc carries a ~38-48 build-day range with assumptions.

